title: For Sale:  Colt Government Lew Horton Special 45ACP Model O1991Z
postcontent: Great old school Colt 1911 45ACP for those that can’t spend a lot of money but want a traditional Colt 1911. Long before there was a Talo, there was Lew Horton. Horton’s daily operations and their special editions have upwards of two decades’ seniority on their friendly competitor neighbors, only 12 miles from each other. Here is the latest Colt Horton’s Special, and it is as traditional as they come. This is a Series 80 descendant of the 1911A1 with firing pin safety, but also with full coverage military style finish, brown Bakelite type GI Grips, and a lanyard ring type Mainspring Housing. Manufacturer is Colt Industries of Hartford, CT. Exclusive distributor is Lew Horton Distributing of Westboro, MA. Colt factory designation is Model O1991Z, M1991A1 Series 80. Construction is entirely steel, with the exception of the grips, and the anodized trigger and mainspring housing. The Colt M1991A1, writes the factory, is a direct 4th generation descendant of the "often imitated but never duplicated" Colt M1911 classic automatic pistol, and this variant is the closest approximation to the World War II version. Type is Browning Design 1911 Government type Single Action semi-automatic pistol. Chambering is .45 ACP Caliber. Barrel is 5 inch stainless, 6 groove left hand 1:16 rifling. Frame and slide finish are matte blue, approximating the WWII parkerized versions. Sight system is matte blue stake on front and dovetailed notch style rear that is drift adjustable only for windage. Safety system is classic threefold, main safety for right handed shooters; grip safety; and Series 80 type firing pin safety. Each 1991 comes with a total of two factory magazines, Colt factory marked and made for Colt by primary supplier Check-Mate. Each magazine holds 7 rounds, so 7 + 1 fully loaded capacity, and 8 shot magazines are readily available from us and throughout the country. Weight empty is 35 ounces with center of gravity at the magazine release. Trigger is .250 serrated face alloy, and the photo specimen pulled in the 6 pound vicinity with minimal felt creep. Each pistol comes in a current production Colt blue box with instruction manual, cable lock, and factory registration paper, total of two magazines, chamber protector, and protective wrapper. Each also contains a total of two grips, one set the pliable black rubber factory Rampant Colt grips and traditional WWII to Vietnam issue type brown plastic. Own a classic without breaking the bank. Shipping is $25 and free for all military, veterans and law enforcement. Please visit and like our FB page at: DCF FB Page

title: For Sale:  1942 Sako Finnish M39 Rifle
location: South Bay L.A., Los Angeles, California
postcontent: This is a 1942 Sako M39 Finnish war horse, it has been there and done that but is in good condition.  The light AZF marking on the hex receiver indicates that this was originally on an M 91 Russian Mosin-Nagant rifle, and later captured by the Austro-Hungarians on the Eastern Front during World War 1. After the war ended the AH Empire broke up, and newly-independent Finland bought up all the Mosins they could to arm themselves, building an M39 from this receiver.Stamped matching receiver, barrel, and floor plate, the buttplate and bolt are not numbered, and the hex receiver's Imperial Eagle has been scrubbed.  A classic Improvement on the Soviet Mosin Nagant, the M39 was one of Finland's mainstay weapons during the Winter and Continuation Wars of World War 2.Chambered in 72x54r, this was made in Riihimaki at SAKO, Suojeluskuntain Ase-ja Konepaja Osakeyhtio (Firearms and Machine Workshop of the Civil Guard).Hey forget about getting Sako's TRG M10, this is much better.The rifle comes with the original sling and cleaning rod.The bore shows use, but still has decent rifling. There is perhaps 60% bluing remaining on the barrel, buttstock, magazine, and little if any left on the well-used receiver.This Sako has its original wartime finger-groove jointed stock, marked with SAKO's gear wheel logo.  The stock shows use but is in good solid condition, and the bore shows some use but still has good rifling.The  picture shows the buttstock's Sako gearwheel cartouche, as well as the stock maker's crossed cannon cartouche with "S", standing for the subcontractor Sakara Oy.There is a tiny Century arms import mark behind the front sight.For local FTF FFL PPT sale in the South Bay LA area, all laws apply, contact me if you want to check it out, thanks for looking.
